[2]
Date: Thu 6 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Antara New Agency, Thu 6 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://www.antara.co.id/en/seenws/?id=6689>

2 other people in Indonesia have reportedly contracted the avian
influenza virus which is blamed for the deadly bird flu disease,
Health Ministry`s disease control and environmental sanitation,
director general I Nyoman Kandun said here today [Thu 6 Oct 2005].
The 2 patients were identified as a 21-year-old resident of Lampung
who had been treated at the Abdul Moeloek general hospital in Lampung
and a 23-year-old resident of Bogor, West Java, who died at the
Sulianti Saroso hospital here few days ago, Kandun said.
Quoting the results of the Reverse Transcription-Polymerase Chain
Reaction (RT-PCR) test of the Research and Development Agency at the
Health Ministry and Jakarta-branch Naval Medical Research Unit
(NAMRU), Kandun said the 2 patients were positively infected with
H5N1 virus which causes the bird flu illness. "Their samples will be
sent to a World Health Organization (WHO) laboratory in Hong Kong for
further confirmation," he said. He also said a team of the Health
Ministry and Atlanta-based Centre for Disease Control and Prevention
(CDC) were conducting investigation in Lampung following the report.
[As of 5 Oct 2005] the Health Ministry [stated that] 75 people in
Indonesia were believed to have contracted the bird flu virus, 11
others were probably infected with the H5N1 virus as they had
laboratory tests showing the tendency [?] of avian influenza virus
infection, and 4 others were confirmed by the WHO laboratory in Hong
Kong to have been infected with avian influenza virus. Another one
reportedly had a positive serological test but did not show clinical
symptoms, the data said. The people who were probably infected with
avian influenza virus were [residents of] Jakarta, Banten, West Java,
North Sumatra, East Kalimantan and Lampung.
According to [Ministry of Health] data, 11 of the people had died
but only 3 of the dead were confirmed to have contracted [avian H5N1
influenza virus infection]. Kandun said all the people were treated
at hospitals the government named as health centers for bird
flu-infected patients. In Jakarta alone, at least 20 people were
treated at Sulianto Saroso hospital as of 4 Oct 2005, he said, adding
that many of them had become sick after visiting the Ragunan Zoo in
South Jakarta.
