[3]
Date: Thu 6 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The People's Daily online, Xinhua report, Thu 6 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200510/06/eng20051006_212847.html>

A 20-month-old baby who was suspected of developing bird flu symptoms finally
died after 3 days of intensive treatment at the Sulianti Saroso Hospital in
Jakarta, a hospital spokesman said Thursday [6 Oct 2005]. The baby died
Wednesday evening due to respiratory problems and worsening pneumonia,
hospital spokesman Ilham Patu was quoted by the Detikcom online news service
as saying. Avian influenza has killed at least 7 people in the country [only 3
so far confirmed by WHO. - Mod.JW]. Indonesian healthcare authorities have
said at least 85 people were hospitalized for developing [avian influenza-
like] symptoms. The Sulianti Saroso Hospital, which is specialized for
patients with infectious diseases, is treating at least 20 suspected bird flu
patients.
******
[4]
Date: Thu 6 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency, Wed 5 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-10/05/content_3584701.htm>

The number of people suspected of having bird flu has doubled to 85
in Indonesia, a government official said here Wednesday [5 Oct 2005].
The cases were dispersed in 9 out of 30 Indonesian provinces, said I
Nyoman Kandun, director general of disease prevention with the
Ministry of Health. Kandun confirmed that 4 patients have tested
positive for bird flu, which [is suspected of having] killed 7
Indonesians so far. The ministry's earlier report put bird flu cases
at 42 nationwide.
******
[5]
Date: Thu 6 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Pravda.ru, Thu 6 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://newsfromrussia.com/world/2005/10/06/64564.html>

Indonesia's Health Minister lowered the country's number of confirmed
human deaths from bird flu to 3 on Thursday, in line with figures
from the WHO. There had been confusion surrounding Indonesia's toll
from bird flu since its 1st death was reported in July 2005, in part
because local laboratory tests were not always consistent. Until
Thursday [6 Oct 2005], Indonesia had reported 6 fatalities from the
virus.
The H5N1 strain of avian influenza has swept through poultry
populations in many parts of Asia since 2003, jumping to humans and
killing at least 62 people region-wide and resulting in the deaths of
tens of millions of birds. Most human cases have been linked to
contact with sick birds. Health Minister Siti Fadilah Supari told
reporters there was only one other confirmed case of bird flu, and
that the patient was recovering.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Reporting by the Indonesian healthcare authorities has confused assessment of
the extent of infection of the human population in Indonesia. Taken together,
these reports indicate that there have been 3 WHO-laboratory confirmed fatal
cases of avian H5N1 infection in Indonesia, one [confirmed] non-fatal case,
and a large number of suspected cases (variously given by Indonesia sources as
up to 75, 85 & 90), which have yet to be confirmed by the WHO-designated
reference laboratory in Hong Kong. - Mod.CP]
